<seg id=1> US Admits Air Attack Killed Hundreds of Iraqi Citizens, UK reporter Says Bombed Site Not Military Target </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Washington, February 13th. On the 13th, the US White House admitted that hundreds of civilians were killed when a multinational air force attacked Baghdad, the capital city of Iraq, but the spokesman persisted that the multinational strike was against a military target. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Fitzwalter, White House spokesman, said that the US government thought it "certainly is a tragedy." </seg>
<seg id=4> He condemned Saddam Hussein, the President of Iraq, who arranged for civilians to be present in the military establishment and thus place them in danger. </seg>
<seg id=5> He said the US considered the target hit to be a direction and control center of the Iraqi army. </seg>
<seg id=6> This establishment "had been coated and disguised to avoid reconnaissance, but proof verifies that it was one of the military targets." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> According to Xinhua News Agency, London, on February 3rd, BBC reporter Bowen stayed in Baghdad.  The capital of Iraq stated that there was no evidence to indicate the  bomb-shelter destroyed by a US bomber was a military target. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The talk given by Bowen on BBC TV news refuted the US government statement that the bomb shelter was a military target. </seg>
<seg id=9> Bowen had an on-site interview and saw the destroyed bomb-shelter, about 400 civilians had been killed. </seg>
</p>
